Plague, marmots - Kyrgystan (Dzhetyoguz) 19980811.1572
Date: 7 Aug 2001 02:01
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited

Plague Breaks out in Mongolia
-----------------------------
About 200 [cases of plague have been reported during the past 2 days. [The
disease is usually caused by physical contact with marmots in this
landlocked country. Teams of doctors have been rushed to the affected areas
in the Central Aymak (the central province) near Ulan Bator and the
southwestern Archangaj Aymag (the Archangaj province), the
Mongolian-language daily Unen (the Truth) said Tuesday.
Measures, including large-scale vaccinations, have been taken to prevent
the plague from further spreading, according to an official with the Center
for Control and Research of Natural Infectious Diseases in Mongolia.
Enkhtuya, a senior medical expert from the center, said: "Almost 90 percent
of the population in the capital city Ulan Bator and about 60 percent in
the areas close to the city have been inoculated against the disease." No
vehicles or persons are allowed to enter or leave the plague-affected areas
under a curfew order issued after the first cases were reported early Monday.
Enough vaccines imported from Russia are available, said Enkhtuya, who
fears a possible outbreak in other provinces.
The outbreak of what is called here the "marmot plague" is not rare in
Mongolia and occurs almost every year in many parts of the country. Marmots
are wild rodents that can spread plague to human beings if people eat the
meat or are bitten by the animal.
The first persons who fell victim to the plague in the latest outbreak are
from 2 herdsmen families who reportedly ate marmot meat. Meanwhile, the
Civil Defense Authority, the Ministry of Nature and Environment, and the
Ministry of Health are considering a nationwide drive to kill marmots,
which is believed to be the most effective way to prevent outbreaks of the
plague.
--
